ObjectLike
public class JsRange
extends DOM2Range.Range.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.Range class.

A JsRange object represents a contiguous range or region of a document, such as the region that the user might select with a mouse drag in a web browser window. If an implementation supports the Range module, the JsDocument object defines a JsDocument.createRange() method that you can call to create a new JsRange object. Be careful, however, IE defines an incompatible JsDocument.createRange() method that returns a nonstandard object similar to, but not compatible with, this class. This class defines a number of methods for specifying a selected region of a document and several more methods for implementing cut-and-paste operations on the selected region.

A range has two boundary points: a start point and an end point. Each boundary point is specified by a combination of a node and an offset within that node. The node is typically an JsElement, JsDocument, or JsText node. For JsElement and JsDocument nodes, the offset refers to the children of that node. An offset of 0 specifies a boundary point before the first child of the node. An offset of 1 specifies a boundary point after the first child and before the second child. If the boundary node is a JsText node, however, the offset specifies a position between two characters of that text.

The properties of a JsRange object provide a way to obtain boundary nodes and offsets of the range. The methods of the class provide a number of ways to set the boundaries of a range. Note that the boundaries of a range may be set to nodes within a JsDocument or a JsDocumentFragment.

Once the boundary points of a range are defined, you can use deleteContents(), extractContents(), cloneContents(), and insertNode(JsNode) to implement cut, copy, and paste operations.

When a document is altered by insertion or deletion, all JsRange objects that represent portions of that document are altered, if necessary, so that their boundary points remain valid and they represent as closely as possible the same document content.

collapse

public final void collapse(java.lang.Boolean toStart)

Collapses this range so that one boundary point is the same as the other.

This method sets one boundary point of the range to be the same as the other point. The point to be modified is specified by the toStart argument. After this method returns, the range is said to be collapsed: it represents a single point within a document and has no content. When a range is collapsed like this, its collapsed property is true.

Parameters:
toStart - If this argument is true, the method sets the end point of the range to the same value as the starting point. Otherwise, it sets the starting point to the same value as the end point.
Since:
1.0

compareBoundaryPoints

public final java.lang.Number compareBoundaryPoints(java.lang.Number how,
                                                    JsRange sourceRange)

Compares a boundary point of the specified range to a boundary point of this range and returns -1, 0, or 1 depending on their order, with the first argument, which must be one of the static constants defined in this class, defining which points to compare.

This method compares a boundary point of this range to a boundary point of the specified sourceRange and returns a value that specifies their relative order in the document source. The how argument specifies which boundary points of each range are to be compared. The legal values for this argument, and their meanings, are as follows:

  • START_TO_START: Compares the start points of the two JsRange nodes.
  • END_TO_END: Compares the end points of the two JsRange nodes.
  • START_TO_END: Compares the start point of sourceRange to the end point of this range.
  • END_TO_START: Compares the end point of sourceRange to the start point of this range.

The return value of this method is a number that specifies the relative position of this range to the specified sourceRange. Therefore, you might expect the range constants for the how argument to specify the boundary point for this range first and the boundary point for sourceRange second. Counterintuitively, however, the Range.START_TO_END constant specifies a comparison of the end point of this range with the start point of the specified sourceRange. Similarly, the Range.END_TO_START constant specifies a comparison of the start point of this range with the end point of the specified range

Parameters:
how - Specifies how to perform the comparison, that is, which boundary points to compare. Legal values are the static constants defined by this class.
sourceRange - The range that is to be compared to this range.
Returns:
The value -1 if the specified boundary point of this range is before the specified boundary point of sourceRange, 0 if the two specified boundary points are the same, or 1 if the specified boundary point of this range is after the specified boundary point of sourceRange.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.WRONG_DOCUMENT_ERR if sourceRange represents a range of a different document than this range does. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

deleteContents

public final void deleteContents()

Deletes the region of the document represented by this range.

This method deletes all document content represented by this range. When it returns, the range is collapsed with both boundary points at the start position. Note that the deletion may result in adjacent JsText nodes that can be merged with a call to JsNode.normalize().

See cloneContents() for a way to copy document content and extractContents() for a way to copy and delete document content in a single operation.

Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.NO_MODIFICATION_ALLOWED_ERR if any portion of the document that is represented by this range is read-only. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsNode.normalize(), cloneContents(), extractContents()

detach

public final void detach()

Tells the implementation that this range will no longer be used and that it can stop keeping track of it.

If you call this method for a range, subsequent method calls or property lookups on that range throw a JsDOMException error with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.INVALID_STATE_ERR.

DOM implementations keep track of all JsRange objects created for a document because they may need to change the range boundary points when the document is modified. When you are certain that a JsRange object isn't needed any more, call this method to tell the implementation that it no longer needs to keep track of that range. Note that once this method has been called for a JsRange object, any use of that range throws an exception. Calling this method is not required but may improve performance in some circumstances when the document is being modified. A JsRange object is not subject to immediate garbage collection.

Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.INVALID_STATE_ERR if it is called on a JsRange object that has already been detached like all JsRange methods. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

insertNode

public final void insertNode(JsNode newNode)

Inserts the specified node into the document at the start point of the range.

This method inserts the specified node and all its descendants into the document at the start position of this range. When it returns, this range includes the newly inserted node. If newNode is already part of the document, it is removed from its current position and then reinserted at the start of the range. If newNode is a JsDocumentFragment node, it is not inserted itself, but all of its children are inserted, in order, at the start of the range

If the node that contains the start of the range is a JsText node, it is split into two adjacent nodes before the insertion takes place. If newNode is a JsText node, it is not merged with any adjacent JsText nodes after it is inserted. To merge adjacent JsText nodes, call JsNode.normalize().

Parameters:
newNode - The node to be inserted into the document.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsRangeException object with the JsRangeException.code property of the value JsRangeException.INVALID_NODE_TYPE_ERR if newNode is an JsAttr, JsDocument, JsEntity, or JsNotation node, or a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.HIERARCHY_REQUEST_ERR if the node that contains the start of the range does not allow children, it does not allow children of the specified type, or newNode is an ancestor of that node, the value JsDOMException.NO_MODIFICATION_ALLOWED_ERR if the node that contains the start of the range or any of its ancestors is read-only, or the value JsDOMException.WRONG_DOCUMENT_ERR if newNode is part of a different document than the range is. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsNode.normalize()
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

surroundContents

public final void surroundContents(JsNode newParent)

Inserts the specified node into the document at the start position of the range and then re-parents all the nodes within the range so that they become descendants of the newly inserted node.

This method re-parents the contents of this range to newParent and then inserts newParent into the document at the start position of the range. It is useful to place a region of document content within a <div> or <span> element.

If newParent is already part of the document, it is first removed from the document, and any children it has are discarded. When this method returns, this range begins immediately before newParent and ends immediately after it.

Parameters:
newParent - The node that is to become the new parent of the contents of this range.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsRangeException object with the JsRangeException.code property of the value JsRangeException.INVALID_NODE_TYPE_ERR if newParent is a JsAttr, JsDocument, JsDocumentFragment, JsDocumentType, JsEntity, JsNotation node, or the value JsRangeException.BAD_BOUNDARYPOINTS_ERR if the range partially selects a node other than a JsText node, so the region of the document it represents cannot be surrounded, or a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.WRONG_DOCUMENT_ERR if newParent and this range were created using different JsDocument objects, the value JsDOMException.NO_MODIFICATION_ALLOWED_ERR if an ancestor of a boundary point of the range is read-only and does not allow insertions, or the value JsDOMException.HIERARCHY_REQUEST_ERR if the container node of the start of the range does not allow children or does not allow children of the type of newParent or newParent is an ancestor of that container node. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
